Looking at this proof goal, I need to show that the maps of two indicator functions (whether `i ∈ X ω` and whether `j ∈ X ω`) are equal under the measure `P`.

Given that `hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P`, which means `HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P`, this tells us that `X` has the Bernoulli distribution on `u` with parameter `p`.

The key insight is that since both `i` and `j` are in `u` (given by `hi` and `hj`), and `X` follows the Bernoulli distribution on `u`, the marginal distributions of whether any particular element of `u` is in `X` should be identical - they are all i.i.d. Bernoulli random variables with parameter `p`.

Looking at the definition of `bernoulliOn`, it's defined as a product measure where each coordinate follows the same distribution (for elements in `u`). The map equality should follow from the fact that both coordinates have the same marginal distribution under this product measure.

Since `hX` gives us that `map X P = Ber(u, p)`, we need to relate the pushforward measures. The composition `map (fun ω => i ∈ X ω) P = map (Set.Mem i) (map X P)`, and similarly for `j`.

```lean
lemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :
    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where
  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop
  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop
  map_eq := by
    simp only [← Measure.map_map (by fun_prop) (by fun_prop)]
    congr 1
    exact hX
```
